        "notes_updates": "Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) - Total range 3-15 | Record best motor response | GCS Eye Opening: 4=Opening spontaneously, 3=Opening to verbal command, 2=Opening to pressure, 1=None | GCS Verbal Response: 5=Coherent speech, 4=Confused disorientated, 3=Words only, 2=Sounds only, 1=None | GCS Motor Response: 6=Obeys commands, 5=Localises painful stimulus, 4=Withdraws from painful stimulus, 3=Flexion to painful stimulus, 2=Extension to painful stimulus, 1=None | GCS <13 on initial assessment OR <15 at 2 hours after injury indicates need for CT | CT Imaging Criteria - Absolute indications: GCS <13 on initial assessment OR <15 at 2 hours after injury | Suspected open/depressed skull fracture/base of skull fracture/facial fractures | Post-traumatic seizure | Two or more episodes of vomiting since head injury | Intubated | Focal neurological deficit | Anticoagulant patients (Warfarin/DOAC): Perform non-contrast CT Brain and C-spine | Relative indications (if LOC or amnesia): Risk factors - Age >65, Bleeding/clotting disorder, Dangerous mechanism, >30min retrograde amnesia | If risk factors present: Perform CT Brain and C-spine | If absent: No imaging required | Dangerous mechanism: Pedestrian/cyclist struck by vehicle, Ejection from vehicle, Fall from height >1m or 5 stairs | Base of skull fracture signs: Raccoon eyes (periorbital ecchymosis), CSF otorrhoea/rhinorrhoea, Battle sign (bruising over mastoid process), Haemotympanum | Neuroprotective measures: Head up 30-45 degrees | MAP >90mmHg unless ICH then MAP >75-80mmHg | Normocarbia PCO2 34-40mmHg (lower end of normal) | Normoxia PaO2 60-100mmHg, O2 sats target >95% | Normothermia (Temp <37.5C) | Normoglycaemia (Blood glucose target 5-10 mmol/l) | Correct electrolyte abnormalities | Monitor for seizures - Phenytoin 20mg/kg IV max rate 50mg/min loading dose in traumatic ICH | Sedation and analgesia to avoid coughing/gagging (raises ICP) | Consider Fentanyl 1-3 mcg/kg over 60 seconds, 3 minutes prior to